english:
  title: Epitaph for Lord An, Master of Virtue and Simplicity, of the Joseon Kingdom in the Ming Era, with Preface
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Lord An bore the name Jongyeon, courtesy name Sacheong, of the An clan from Suneung. His father, Lord Chuk, known as Master Geungjae, passed the civil examination under the Yuan and served Goryeo as Grand Councillor and Minister of State. Upon his death, he received the posthumous title of Master Munjeong. The collection he compiled during his tenure as Commissioner of the Eastern Provinces remains in circulation today.

    His grandfather, Lord Seok, achieved high rank through examination. His great-grandfather, Lord Huiseo, served as District Magistrate, accumulating virtue without expenditure, leaving blessings for descendants. Master Munjeong, through diligent study, rose from humble origins to the highest office. He married the Lady of Gamcheon, of the Mun clan, daughter of the Inspector of the Military Arsenal.

    Lord An was born in the fifth lunar month on a day of great auspiciousness. From birth, he displayed brilliance and keen intelligence. As he grew, he devoted himself to learning, spurning idle games. His bearing distinguished him from common children; men of wisdom knew he was destined for greatness.

    At seventeen, during the civil examination overseen by Left Commissioner Kim Gwangjae, where Minister Yi Eom and Councillor Jeong Eulbo conducted the literary trials, Lord An was among the first to achieve passage. In early Imgo, he became Provisional Examiner of the National Academy, and after three years, received permanent appointment. In Eulyu, he was selected for the Hall of Worthies and Spring-Autumn Institute, serving as Junior Compiler. The scholars in this hall had previously been known for their lax habits; Lord An reformed them through propriety and law, bringing proper decorum to the office.

    In Byeongsu, he received additional ranks as Reviser and Court Official. When his term concluded and he was due for promotion, his senior colleague Shim Dongro, though advanced in years, held a lower position. Lord An yielded his place, allowing the elder to advance first. When Master Munjeong heard this, he rejoiced, saying: "Yielding is virtue's first principle. When I yield to others, who would abandon me? Our family has such a person; surely our line will flourish." Within a year, Lord An was appointed to the Board of Censors.

    Thereafter, he advanced through ranks—Deputy of the Granary of Preparedness, Vice Director of Imperial Stables, and Director of Public Works—each post reflecting his competence, and his reputation spread widely. When King Gongmin ascended the throne, Lord An was appointed Vice Minister of Personnel. In Imjin, he advanced to Vice Director of Military Affairs. In Gyesa, he rose to Chief of the Board of Laws. All matters of land disputes and slavery cases fell under this office, and Lord An judged them with perfect fairness, earning acclaim for his clarity.

    In autumn of Gapgo, at thirty years of age, Lord An was selected as Inspector of Gyeongsang Province. On the day of his farewell audience, the King asked about the principles of governing the people. Lord An expounded with greater detail and earnestness than other inspectors, and the King praised him. His administration indeed earned widespread commendation. That winter, he transferred to the Ministry of Lands. In Eulmi, appointed as Major of Military Affairs bound for Yeohung, he encountered his mother's passing and did not assume the post.

    In summer of Bingsin, when the King executed the treacherous relatives of the deposed Queen Gi, he raised Lord An to Censor-in-Waiting to restore the vigor of law and governance. In Jeongyu, he became Scrivener and Court Diarist. Through a memorial, he was reassigned to Minister of Rites. In Musul, he transferred to the Ministry of Personnel. When the Political Bureau was abolished and its functions transferred to the Ministries of Personnel and Military Affairs, Lord An managed these duties with such impartiality that even his colleagues feared his integrity.

    In Gyeongja, he attained the rank of Grand Master of Court Protocol and Censor-in-Waiting. In autumn of Sinchuk, he went as Inspector to the Yangguang region. That winter, when the Red Turban bandits invaded Seoul and King Gongmin fled southward, Lord An proceeded to Chungju to prepare the royal provisions. Among the King's attendants was one who bore him ill will and slandered him to the monarch, saying: "Inspector An has reached Chungju but has already crossed the ridge and fled." The King believed this falsehood and sent an official to apprehend him. When the messenger arrived at Chungju, he found Lord An in the official residence, diligently preparing provisions, and recognized the slander. Learning the truth, he brought Lord An back and reported the matter. The King released him without further inquiry. Yet the courtiers slandered him again, and he was imprisoned. Only through the intervention of the Prime Minister, who declared his innocence, was he appointed Governor of Cheongpung, which he left after a year. To this day, the people of that region remember him fondly.

    In Gyemyo, he was appointed Chief Minister of Personnel. In Gapjin, he advanced to Chief of the Board of Laws. When Shin Don seized power—earning the title of Premier—the literati competed to attach themselves to his favor. One official told Lord An: "Certain persons have recommended you to the Premier; you could become Censor. It would be wise to visit him promptly." Lord An declined, saying: "I am by nature retiring and negligent; I am incapable of courting influence." Shamed, the official instead slandered Lord An, causing him to be sent as Governor of Gangneung. Though he administered with compassion, he was soon replaced. Lord An then lived in seclusion for seven or eight years, withdrawing from public life and amusing himself with classics and poetry.

    When Shin Don was executed in Hongwu's xinhai year, in the second lunar month of Renzi, Lord An was restored as Censor-in-Waiting. That winter, he received an additional appointment as Chief Librarian. In Guiyou, he was promoted to Vice Minister of Personnel, Court Diarist, and Custodian of the Precious Writings with responsibility for the Spring-Autumn Institute. In Jiayin, he became Senior Vice Minister of Personnel. In Yimao, he served successively as Great Rector of the National Academy, Director of the Bureau of Imperial Relatives, and received the rank of Eminent Counselor of the Right.

    In Bingchen spring, he was appointed Great Censor, receiving the title of Eminent Guardian. That autumn, he entered the Privy Council as Director of Studies while continuing as Great Censor. Shortly after, he was transferred to Deputy Director of the Privy Council. In Dingsi, he received the additional rank of Coadjutor. In Wuwu, he became Counselor. In Jimei, he was promoted to Grand Master of Harmony and Director of the Bureau of Auspicious Rites, and subsequently received additional honors. In Gisa, at age sixty, he was elevated to Senior Councillor and Director of the Ministry of Lands—the realm celebrated him as one of two great ministers. As envoy to the great country, he congratulated the imperial court. Returning that winter, when the Reverential Young Lord ascended the throne, he was appointed Great Director of the Hall of Worthies and Spring-Autumn Institute.

    In Gyeonggo, he became Director of the Three Departments and received the titles of Major Military Officer and Controller of the Astronomical Bureau. In Sinmi, he was promoted to Grand Master of Harmony and enfeoffed as Prince of Xingning. He repeatedly requested retirement on account of his eminence and years.

    In Imshin, when our present King ascended the throne in the seventh lunar month, recognizing Lord An as an elder statesman of this dynasty, of unsullied virtue and commanding respect sufficient to stabilize both the refined and common folk, he was appointed Grand Master of Benevolence, Preceptor of the State, Director of the Three Departments, and Grand Scholar of the Hall of Worthies. In Guiyou, he became Director of the Ministry of Personnel. In Jiawu, at seventy years of age, he was again sent in the second month as envoy to the great country. Arriving at Lianshanstation, the Liaodong command, claiming imperial orders, prevented his passage, and he returned. On the twenty-fourth day of the third month, stricken with illness, he passed away at his residence.

    When word reached the court, the King was deeply grieved and suspended the audience. He dispatched the Left Minister and Earl of Pyongyang Zhao Jun, bearing an imperial letter, to make offerings at the bier and present gifts of condolence exceeding the norm. The Ministry of Rites posthumously titled him Master of Refined Simplicity.

    Lord An possessed a grave and dignified nature, with bearing both serene and luminous. In his conduct, he was circumspect; in his office, diligent. In his household, he spoke not of profit. When facing matters, he remained tranquil and composed, never displaying haste or perturbation of countenance. In receiving others, the higher his station grew, the more humble he became. He never spoke of others' failings, yet praised their virtues without ceasing. In instructing his sons and grandsons, he began always with the principle of avoiding false speech.

    His eldest son Jungon served as Governor of Andong and received from him dozens of written admonitions, detailed and earnest, suitable as models for all. Lord An constructed a pavilion on the hill behind his residence, inscribing it with the name "Dual Clarity," by which he called himself. When guests arrived, he invariably offered wine, yet sought neither luxury nor excess. He took no pleasure in stringed instruments, delighting instead in propriety of heart and genuine welcome.

    Twice he oversaw the selection of officials, yet never permitted private solicitation. Though he moved among the remonstrance officials, he addressed himself to fundamentals, not trifles. Through successive reigns, he held the highest offices, yet never sought favor or reward for his children. He faithfully maintained established institutions and disliked sudden changes. His discourse was marked by generous forbearance—the bearing of a true minister.

    When Privy Councillor Zhao Yunyl became Governor of Gangneung some twenty years after Lord An's time there, learning that the old men of that region remembered him with undiminished fondness, he built a shrine and had Lord An's portrait hung therein. Upon Lord An's passing, all, whether near or far, learned of his death with genuine sorrow. Thus we may say Lord An's end was as noble as his beginning.

    Lord An married the daughter of Eminent Guardian and Right Counselor Kim Hwinam, with whom he had four sons and one daughter. His eldest, Jungon, held the rank of Eminent Guardian, served as Director of the Privy Council and Hall of Worthies, and attained the rank of Senior Guard. He married the daughter of Minister of Lands Kim Anli but had no son, passing before his father.

    His second son, Gyeongryang, now serves as Grand Master and Inspector of the Northwest Frontier and member of the Privy Council. Once serving as Privy Councillor observing the Yangguang region, he gained renown. The King, valuing the northwest territories, wished to appoint capable administrators but found candidates scarce; the court recommended Lord An's son, who was thus selected. His third son, Gyeongjeong, bears the titles of Loyal Guardian and Grand Master, enfeoffed as Prince of Xingning. He served as Great Censor while observing Jeolla Province. All three sons passed the examination. Their mother, Lady Kim, was enfeoffed as Mistress of Gyeongnyeong and received annual stipends from the state; through her son's merit, these honors continue undiminished.

    The fourth son, Gyeonggeom, holds the rank of Eminent Master and Director of Public Works. He has served in the remonstrance offices and observed the provincial administrations, earning recognition for his talents. All the sons upheld their father's teachings—modest, conscientious, and respectful of propriety. The daughter married Lord You Hu, a man of upright character, proving a worthy match for Lord An's family.

    The three eldest sons have children of their own. Gyeongryang married the daughter of Lord Yang Cheonryong but had no son; his second wife of the Jeong clan bore him Minsu. Gyeongjeong married the daughter of Counselor Jeong Sado and had one son, Sun, who serves as Junior Custodian. Gyeonggeom married the daughter of Lord Han Soo of Cheongseong and had one son, Mindong, who serves as Deputy Superviser of the Granary, and five daughters. The eldest daughter married Court Official Kim Maengseong; the second married Examiner Yi Yunshang; the third married Court Official Kim Cheol; the fourth married Commander Yi Saheun; the youngest are still young.

    Lord You had two sons: the elder, Yi, serves as Junior Remonstrator; the younger, Han, serves as Deputy Commander. The grandchildren are numerous. Lord An's grandson Sun married the daughter of Counselor Jeong Mungwon and has two sons and two daughters, still young: the eldest named Sungik, the second Sungseon. The elder of these served as Junior Remonstrator and married the daughter of Privy Councillor Yi Jongdeok, having two sons: the elder Bangseon, the younger Banggyeong. In a second marriage to the daughter of Director of Records Fang Sun, he had one son, Banggeun. The younger grandson Han married the daughter of Great Censor Park Gyeong and had one son. Kim Maengseong had two daughters, still young.

    In the summer following Lord An's burial, his son the Prince of Xingning came on behalf of the lady dowager and said to the author: "My father's virtue and conduct are widely known and cannot be concealed. We wish to ensure his memory endures forever, committing it to stone for posterity. You have long kept company with my brothers, shared in learning with them, advanced in official rank together, and have long known my father's deeds. Moreover, you now serve in the Hall of Worthies and Spring-Autumn Institute in editorial capacity. You must not decline to compose this epitaph." The author, lacking great talent, dared not refuse.

    The epitaph reads:

    High mountains rise in grandeur,
    Circling the land of Suneung,
    Where pure essence gathered,
    And celestial grace descended,
    Bearing forth a man of noble bearing—
    Gentle and reverent in his way.

    Officially exalted without interruption,
    Blessed with seventy winters of life,
    Fine his beginning, finer still his end,
    With sons and grandsons to carry on,
    The halls filled with their distinction—
    All the fruit of teaching and guidance.

    On Seoguk's verdant hillside,
    There stands his great burial mound,
    The resting place of his immortal soul.
    We have carved stone and raised monument,
    Inscribing these words upon it,
    To endure forever more.
  footnotes:
    - Suneung (順興) was an important administrative region in medieval Korea, the ancestral home of the An clan.
    - The Yuan Dynasty civil examination system (制科) was a prestigious avenue for advancement; Lord An's father's success in this examination facilitated the family's rise.
    - The Hall of Worthies and Spring-Autumn Institute were elite scholarly institutions responsible for compilation of records and literary matters.
    - Shin Don was a powerful eunuch-administrator during the Goryeo-early Joseon period whose eventual execution marked a significant political upheaval.
    - The Red Turban bandits were Ming-era pirates and rebel forces that threatened Korean coastal and inland regions during this era.
    - The Northwest Frontier (西北面) refers to the sensitive border regions with the Jurchen peoples and later the Qing, posts of strategic importance.
    - The postposition "君" (gun/prince) refers to honorary titles of nobility; Lord An held several such enfeoffments throughout his career without territorial holdings.
    - The author of this epitaph is Gwon Geun (權近), a younger contemporary who served in similar literary and administrative capacities.
